  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA32-kiḷavi">itu talaivikkuk kuṟai nayappak kūṟiyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is what was said to HER about granting [his] request.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA32">
<l>            māyō ṉaṉṉa mālvaraik kavāaṉ</l>
<l>            vāliyō ṉaṉṉa vayaṅkuveḷ ḷaruvi</l>
<l>            yammalaik kiḻavō ṉannayan teṉṟum</l>
<l>            varuntiṉa ṉeṉpatōr vāyccoṟ ṟēṟāy</l>
<l>            nīyuṅ kaṇṭu numaroṭu meṇṇi </l>
<l>            yaṟivaṟin taḷaval vēṇṭu maṟutaraṟ</l>
<l>            kariya vāḻi tōḻi periyōr</l>
<l>            nāṭi naṭpi ṉallatu</l>
<l>            naṭṭu nāṭārtam moṭṭiyōr tiṟattē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Although they said that the lord of the mountain pretty</l>
<l rend="indent2">with waterfalls, glowing white like the white one,</l>
<l rend="indent2">on the mountain side, black like the black one,<note place="foot">The black one and the white one are, according to T.V.G., Kṛṣṇa and Bālarāma (cf. one parallel in PN 38.14ff.).</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">longed for us<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nayant’ eṉṟum</term>: abs. + <term xml:lang="ta">eṉ</term> might be regarded as a way of embedding indirect speech. One possible parallel for this would be KT 207.7 <term xml:lang="ta">ceṉṟeṉak kēṭṭanam mārvalar palarē</term>, where <term xml:lang="ta">ceṉṟu</term> refers to the fact that HE has left, which has been heard by those who are close to HER.</note>,</l>
<l>you don't believe<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tērāy</term> can also be read as participial noun and apposition to <term xml:lang="ta">nīyum</term>.</note> the true words that say “he has suffered”.</l>
<l rend="indent">After you've seen [him] too, considering [what you saw] with your people,</l>
<l>it is necessary to know [and] weigh the knowledge.</l>
<l rend="indent3">Difficult</l>
<l>to refuse completely<note place="foot">Thus the nuance of <term xml:lang="ta">maṟu-taral</term>? (According to the TL <term xml:lang="ta">maṟutā</term> is equivalent to <term xml:lang="ta">maṟu</term>.)</note>, oh friend, [are] they.</l>
<l rend="indent">Other than considering friendships thoroughly [beforehand],<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nāṭi naṭpiṉ allatu</term>: how to account for the abs. <term xml:lang="ta">nāṭi</term> in such a position, where we would expect a peyareccam?</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">[once] established,</l>
<l>those bound [by them] don’t consider<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nāṭar tam</term>: what can be the function of <term xml:lang="ta">tam</term>, following the verb here?</note> the issue [anymore].</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="3+4b">
    <l>You don’t believe the true words that say: “longing always for us</l>
    <l>he has suffered, the man from…”</l>
</lg>
        </lg>
         </div>
